text:
hi, my name is roxanne darling (@roxannedarling) and this is my week to takeover instagram from the los angeles center of photography (lacp) @la_centerofphoto. i am an emerging artist currently living in santa fe, nm. i love that lacp welcomes out-of-state photographers to be part of their community. this week, let's talk about bodies, nature, and getting older!

image: 
i am: saying goodbye to my merchandized self

the photos iâ€™m sharing this week are of me, from my series of portraits in nature. as a 66-year-old woman and emerging artist, iâ€™m exploring the:
* the natural desire to be unclothed outdoors, in the privacy of precious places;
* a newly discovered quality of self-acceptance for my aging self;
* an appetite to create art from the female gaze, as a type of reclaiming my time, my body, and my point of view.

the photos were taken in 2017-2018 on an extended rv trip around the western us with my partner. in many cases, the place itself spoke up first and invited me to explore ways of finding myself in nature. as a card-carrying member of the #metoo movement, i hope this work conveys a type of freedom of self-expression that is possible regardless of oneâ€™s painful past experiences.

the photos were shot using several cameras: iphone, dji drone, and a canon dslr. all images have been cropped square; some images have been slightly modified to meet instagram rules. *
*
*
#lacpinstagramtakeover #lacp #losangelescenterofphotography #lacpmember #lacenterofphoto #womenphotographers #picoftheday #iam #santafeartist #freethinker

text: feb 23. "how could you say such a thing? that's so- it's so wrong! i mean, remember the way he all taught astronomy in high school? it was so much fun." "of course it was fun. i wasn't bashing on astronomy. it inspired me to get my phd remember?" "exactly! and he did that. he helped you become who you are today." "he doesn't deserve credit for all that i am. he was an influence in my life, just like everyone else has been. i'm not saying he was a bad teacher. i'm saying he was a bad person. those aren't mutually exclusive." "i just can't believe you would do such a thing. everyone will learn the truth once word gets out. you are going to ruin everything for him. what about his family? his three kids? i've babysat them!" "so what? they can learn the truth from someone else? or so that they can learn he likes to touch kids from their own experience? i'm done protecting him. and even if you don't believe, someone will." "they are just going to call you crazy!" text:
*trigger warning to the beautiful humans in my life* 
years ago a guy i thought was a friend did some pretty shitty things. as a result of his actions he was kicked out of the program we were apart of. he called me in tears several days before his flight asking me was what he did "really that bad?" he made me seriously question myself, after all, it could have been much worse. i ended the conversation telling him that he wasn't a bad guy and saying i'm sorry he had to leave. the night before he was sent home we hung out as a group.  he caught me at the table and tried to convince me that what he did was "not that bad" it was not "sexual harassment" and " i know what sexual harassment is..." i distinctly remember the whiteness of my knuckles as i stared at them holding the table to stop the shaking. i distictly remember my fear and my confusion. i distinctly remember blaming myself. years ago a guy i thought was a friend did some pretty shitty things. today a friend from the program started a group chat. the guy shared his good news about his happy life, i felt genuinely happy for him, everyone deserves happiness, but i did not respond. years ago a guy i thought was a friend did some pretty shitty things. today in our group chat he posted this. my heart raced. years ago a guy i thought was a friend did some shitty things. fuck. it was still raw. years ago a guy i thought was a friend did some shitty things. my stomach was in knots. years ago a guy i thought was a friend did some shitty things.  #metoo

she's been trapped for over a year in a foreign country,  alone and struggling whilst healing from years of rape and torture.  please help bring nara home and sign her petition:

text:
8 mart'a takipcilerime ozel sadece hanimlara kanali oldugum ra sheeba enerjisi calismasi yapilacaktir. kayit icin dm .

ra sheeba calismasi oncesi dikkat edilmesi gereken hususlar:
.

1. ilik dus aliniz.
2. kahve asitli icecek alkol vb tuketmeyiniz.
3. calismaya katilacaginiz odayi arindiriniz. ( tutsu sirkeli su ile silme adacayi defne vs yakma dua okuma havalandirma vb).
4.o gunu sakin ve sevgi dolu gecirmeye niyet ediniz.
5. yardima ihtiyaci olan birine maddi/manevi bir yardimda bulununuz.
6.bol su tuketiniz.
7. calisma sirasinda los bir ortamda, mum, tutsu, tuz lambasi vs yakabilir, meditatif muzikler calabilirsiniz.
8. ortami elektromanyetik cihazlardan arindiriniz.
9. calisma 23.00 de baslayacak 30 dk surecektir.
10. calisma suresince uzanmanizda fayda vardir. olumlamalar yapabilir dua edebilirisiniz. kimsenin rahatsiz etmeyecegi bir odada olmaniz yararinizadir. calisma esnasinda uykuya dalabilirsiniz. endise etmeyin. hala sifalanmaya hatta daha yogun sifalanmaya gecmissinizdir.
11. bu calisma her calismads oldugu gibi farkindaligi artirmaya niyet eder. o nedenle calisma sonrasinda da farkinda olmaya anda kalmaya dikkat ediniz. haberci ruyalariniz olabilir. cevrenizdeki herseye ve herkese dikkat etmelisiniz ki ilahi mesajin nereden gelecegi bilinmez ğŸ˜‰ğŸ˜‰ğŸ˜‰
12. calisma sonrasinda tesekkur etmeyi sukretmeyi unutmayiniz..sukredelim ki sukrettiklerimizin sayisi artsin. ve unutmayalim ki istedigimiz ne varsa once ona layik oldugumuzu kabul edelim. cunku bilincaltinizda layik hissetmediginiz hic bir esya/mal/is/dua/bereket/ask/evlilik/cocuk akliniza ne gelirse bize gelmeyecektir.
.

text:
#ynaijanewestablishment: damilola marcus makes the ynaija new establishment list, 2019
.
damilola marcus (market march)
.

damilola marcus, or omogedami as she is more commonly referred to, is relatively new to the activism space. but her impact has been no less vital to the growing agitation for a re-evaluation of normalized behaviour in interpersonal relationships between men and women in nigeria. as part of a new wave of feminists who have taken their message online, marcus routinely engages in ranging conversations about the problems and needs of women in nigerian patriarchal society, garnering a strong following but also many detractors who see her defiance and passion for womenâ€™s rights as intimidating. ms. marcus doesnâ€™t pay either her fans or detractors any mind, focused as she is on creating safe spaces for women to express themselves without the threat of violence or intimidation. .
.
in 2018, ms. marcus was one of the facilitators of the nigerian #metoo movement that saw teenage girls from a number of high-profile nigerian secondary schools detail abuse, rape and sexual harassment that happen with these institutions. having so many young women feel like they were given a space to express themselves encouraged marcus to take her activism offline and start â€˜market marchâ€™, inspired by the routine complaints of sexual harassment by traders in lagos markets. in late 2018, market march organized its first offline protest march, choosing the notorious yaba and tejuosho market as its test grounds. though met with initial backlash, testimonials suggest that ms. marcus and market march made significant impact on the men of the market. .
.
while most people know damilola marcus as omogedami the feminist activist, ms. marcus is also an accomplished brand strategist and graphic designer, running a design label with her associate seyi olusanya. she also volunteers for organizations like stand to end rape and sanitary aid for nigerian girls.

text:
i was engaged at hearst castle and it was a place i had given up, it was too painful to consider going back for so many years. yesterday i went back with my brother 
trauma and pain don't heal themselves in my experience... time doesn't heal everything as we are told to believe. in order for me to return to this area and have gratitude for my pain is the biggest accomplishment of my life and only possible because of my sobriety, my commitment to my health and wellness. a tremendous amount of personal effort to transform and change myself allowed me to return with no sadness! 
letting go of the past and worrying about the future used to be how i spent my time until i realized that i have no control over anything but my reaction to life. it's so much better than to be stuck in denial, stuck in the past, wishing things could have been different.  now i know that the past can't be changed, no matter how much i want it to and to focus on the present moment. 
one of my favorite poems captures my feelings perfectly.... "tomorrow the sun will rise, either in splendour or behind a mask of clouds â€“ but it will rise. until it does we have no stake in tomorrow for it is as yet unborn.

this leaves only one day â€“ today â€“ any man or woman can only fight the battles of one day. itâ€™s only when you or i add the burdens of those awful eternities â€“ yesterday and tomorrow â€“ that we break down.

it is not the experience of today that drives people mad â€“ it is the remorse or bitterness of yesterday or the dread of what tomorrow may bring.

so therefore let us live but one day at a time"

text:
so imma say it.
i'm so sick of this divine feminine kick. sick of only female me too stories. sick of only women talking about abuse and rape from men.

when will there be pages about the healthy divine masculine and it's importance and power? when will we talk about the path and pleasure of a male tantric? when will we discuss men who have been raped and abused by both men and women? when will we let men embrace femininity instead of just women embracing their inner masculinity?

the world caters to men but only in the most superficial empty ways. when it comes to being emotionally well, healing, being spiritual, and having artistic expression, women are always the ones who get to do this feverishly. 
men take the time to heal and be yourself in the deepest of ways. feel deeply, be vulnerable, please! and women please help our men do this! it's their job to heal and grow but as friends, mothers, sisters, lovers, you should help your male friends find themselves and help them heal just like you help other girls.

text:
ğŸ¬ 1. woman of substance by kaley isabella // 2. ballad of a female taxi driver from beirut  by naomi moser // 3. be bold for change by the progress film company // 4.  women empowerment mural by sober

as i was looking for empowering art vidÃ©os to share, i realised that women empowerment is often only associated to gender based violence and i think it is problematic, of course those are very important issues that require awareness but it also give the perception and the narrative that only represent women as victims in need of saving from evil men.

womenâ€™s reluctance to identify with feminism has nothing to do with superficial reasons like branding. feminists should be asking themselves why so many women arenâ€™t willing to join them under the feminist banner. one of the main reason why so many are just not interested in feminism is that it no longer seeks to make women free. instead, it treats women as vulnerable beings in need of protection from the outside world and implies that life for women in the 21rst century is unbearable and oppressive putting the emphasize on our short comings instead of on all our acheivements. western women, who are in a very privileged position compared to their sisters globally, are stereotyping themselves asÂ damsels in distressÂ incapable of functioning in the adult world, and in permanent need of rescuing.Â itâ€™s as senseless as it is damaging a create a vicious circle. feminism is all about empowering women, but how can a woman be empowered when constantly undermined as a victim of rape culture, patriarchy , sexism and so on? 
there has been a cultural shift within feminism which has shifted the aim from female empowerment to status-by-victimhood. which threatens to undo the progress made for women, valorise fragility, discourage resilience, weaponise victimhood and fatally undermine gender relations. itâ€™s not good for women to be treated as fragile victims rather than competent actors in the public sphere. itâ€™s not good for either sex for men to become afraid that talking to women, complimenting women, criticising women, flirting with women or touching women in friendly greeting could destroy their lives.

text:
i have always loved kesha. when i was a teenage alcoholic that couldnâ€™t figure out how to love myself this woman gave me anthems to throw glitter to and disconnect from my pain.
during my college years, struggling with bulimia, i played the warrior album on repeat knowing this woman was fighting the same battle. 
having experienced sexual misconduct by someone close to me, my heart ached with this woman when she took her fight to capitol hill on behalf of all women. as far as iâ€™m concerned, this woman sparked the #metoo movement. 
as a person that never quite fit the profile of heterosexually i cried watching kesha accept the @humanrightscampaign visibility award.
when the video for praying came out, my heart stood still hearing her discuss suicide with such bravery. i listened to her recite thoughts that had passed through my own mind more times than i could count when seeking sobriety and recovery. 
i let tears fall during the rainbow tour as she showed us the beautiful magic you can create from the darkness as long as you keep choosing to fight!
@iiswhoiis i can not thank you enough for the loving space you created for your animals on the cruise. i have never seen or felt so much fearless love in one place. i have never felt so at home or so brave and it all happened amongst a ship full of strangers. 
thank you for holding my hand, looking me in the eyes, and reminding me to take my recovery one day at a time. 
forever my magical rainbow idol ğŸŒˆ #keshacruise

text:
//#itoowasmolested by my brother!//
.
.
â€œhome is believed to be the safest place where you are always in the shelter of your family, father, mother, and brother. it is ironic how the place you are supposed to me safest turned into a nightmare for me. i was living in a nuclear family where my father was away making a living for a very long time while mom used to go out with her friends often in the night. i was left alone with my brother at home in those days when it all started. .
.
he used to invite me to his room to show adult movies leaving me uncomfortable. he asked me to act like what we just saw while instructing me to stay quiet about how he touches me or else he will get me thrown out of the house by our parents. i faced this all for some two years. the aftermaths were my dual attempts of suicide and breaking down in front of a psychologist. i am still unable to share it with my parents! i think this is the reality of every girl. all i can do is to hope for the world to be safer and better in the times to come.â€
.
shall one tell her parents about molestation? share your views in comments! .
.

text:
so few days back we were having a general discussion on dos and donts of an interview. one of the female colleagues shared her experience that  women have to be very careful about what we wear to our interviews because she had a bad experience once. this grabbed everyone's attention and we asked her what had happened. she did not even start to speak when one of the guy spoke his heart out... 'stop your metoo drama', he said and laughed casually. 
well, do you see anything funny here? no right? i thought the same... i did not know that we still have so many so-called educated men in our society who think that metoo moment is trash and its only a perception when we say that we live in a patriarchal society.

i asked him if he knew what was he talking about... to which he replied, 'oho! now you girls would attack me.' it is so disappointing that even today we have to share our experiences with everyone to tell them we face harassment every day since our childhood. yet, they don't believe us and label us as an attention seeker or would call it a publicity stunt.

our own uncle molested us when we were young in our own house, our school driver groped us while dropping us to the school, our father-like men stare at us in the market, our tutors harass us and what not.. these are not mere stories. i am sharing my friends' and my own experiences.

so dear men and women when next time someone is opening up and speaking to you about such experiences, please try to console them and listen to them instead of mocking them and shattering their confidence. we have a lot of molesters around us please do not  support them.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
...
.
.

.

.

.

text:
kanwal ahmed founded the facebook group â€œsoul sisters pakistanâ€ with the focused purpose of cultivating a safe space for pakistani women to talk about their day to day concerns, and have the empathic, invested responses of the other women. they share posts as diverse as the excitement of buying new bangles, relatable memes, funny family mishaps to heartbreaking life tragedies. a lot of women shared their stories of harassment and rape on this forum at the peak of the #metoo movement, and as a result, several women opened up about it in the comments. in a culture where so many pakistani brothers were shocked at their sisters posting a #metoo status on facebook, soul sisters pakistan provided a safe and secure haven for several women brimming with their own stories of harassment and abuse. 
this is kanwal ahmadâ€™s passion project and full time job- she doesnâ€™t approve more than 200 posts daily, and ensures that the posts donâ€™t get shared out of the group. she has a strict ethical policy too, and has successfully created a very comfortable space. sheâ€™s one of the two pakistanis (both women!) selected for facebookâ€™s first community leadership program in 2018.

aurat march is about cultivating an empowered sisterhood between pakistani women, and kanwal ahmedâ€™s brainchild â€œsoul sisters pakistanâ€ is one such desperately needed platform that cultivates strength through the exclusive connection that we women can offer to each other.

#everydayheroines #auratmarchlahore #humaurtain #soulsisterspakistan

text:
according to the national sexual violence resource center * 1 in 5 women and 1 in 71 men will be raped at some point in their lives.
* in the united stares 1 in 3 women and 1 in 6 men experienced some form of contact sexual violence in their lifetime.
* 51.1% of female victims of rape reported being raped by an intimate partner and 40.8% by an acquaintance.
* 52.4% of male victims report being raped by an acquaintance and 15.1% by a stranger.
* 49.5% of multiracial women and over 45% of american indian/alaska native women were subjected to some form of contact sexual violence in their lifetime.
* 91% of victims of rape and sexual assault are female, and 9% are male * in 8 out of 10 cases of rape, the victim knew the perpetrator.
* 8% of rapes occur while the victim is at work. 
the problem of sexual violence runs rampant, and yet rape is the most under-reported crime; 63% of sexual assaults are not reported to police. of the remaining 37% that are reported less than 10% are instances of false reporting. the facts are clear, and still the culture that would rather victims of sexually based crimes remain silent prevails. 
join rebecca macceile as she throws off the shackles of silence and raises her voice. turquoise boot straps: a survivorâ€™s thoughts provides a glimpse into her journey of self discovery while tackling many controversial topics at the height of the metoo era. #comingsoon #nonfiction #metoo #writingcommunity #authorsofinstagram #indiepublishing #linkinbio

text:
hi, my name is roxanne darling (@roxannedarling) and this was my week to takeover instagram from the los angeles center of photography (lacp) @la_centerofphoto. i am an emerging artist currently living in santa fe, nm. i love that lacp welcomes out-of-state photographers to be part of their community. 
this is my last post. i am grateful for the opportunity to share my work with you. you can find me @roxannedarling and my website is roxannedarling.com. keep in touch! thank you, lacp!

image: 
i am: sitting with my sweet and thorny memories

the photos iâ€™m sharing this week are of me, from my series of portraits in nature. as a 66-year-old woman and emerging artist, iâ€™m exploring the: * the natural desire to be unclothed outdoors, in the privacy of precious places; * a newly discovered quality of self-acceptance for my aging self; * an appetite to create art from the female gaze, as a type of reclaiming my time, my body, and my point of view.

the photos were taken in 2017-2018 on an extended rv trip around the western us with my partner. in many cases, the place itself spoke up first and invited me to explore ways of finding myself in nature. as a card-carrying member of the #metoo movement, i hope this work conveys a type of freedom of self-expression that is possible regardless of oneâ€™s painful past experiences.

the photos were shot using several cameras: iphone, dji drone, and a canon dslr. all images have been cropped square; some images have been slightly modified to meet instagram rules. *
*
*

text:
final hours for viewing jane anger by @rosemarymezadesplas at amos eno gallery. pictured here: â€œyo tambienâ€ hand-seen gray human hair on black twill fabric, 25x21x2â€ .
come to #56bogart and catch the exhibition before itâ€™s gone! closing at 6pm today, sunday, february 24.
jane anger features hand-sewn human hair drawings, watercolors and onsite installations. rosemary meza-desplasâ€™ figurative artworks emphasize line and movement. the title refers to a 16th century pamphlet published in england titled jane anger, her protection for women.

meza-desplas explores the concept of anger as a tool for change by juxtaposing found imagery from social media, art history and mass media. she is interested in how the social movements, womenâ€™s marches and #metoo, harnessed anger in order to forefront an array of gender-based burdens. 
this exhibition includes meza-desplasâ€™ most recent drawings which incorporate her gray hair. she has been sewing with her own hair since 2000. her hair is hand-sewn into a variety of grounds with small embroidery needles. meza-desplasâ€™ decision to collect, sort and utilize hair as a vehicle for art-making is informed by socio-cultural symbolism, feminism and body issues, and religious symbolism. hair embodies a dichotomy: it can be sexy and engaging to people, on the other hand, it can be repulsive â€“ like a hair in your soup or a hair on your hotel pillow. 
there are religious connotations to hair which coincide with symbolism reflecting strength, sensuality and reverence; such as delila cutting off samsonâ€™s hair and mary magdalen washing the feet of jesus with her hair.

gop is dead. gop remains dead. and we have killed him. how shall we comfort ourselves, the murderers of all murderers? what was holiest and mightiest of all that the world has yet owned has bled to death under our knives: who will wipe this blood off us? what water is there for us to clean ourselves? what festivals of atonement, what sacred games shall we have to invent? is not the greatness of this deed too great for us? must we ourselves not become gods simply to appear worthy of it?

howlindsey doody

one year ago...
 hollywood's biggest night took time to deliver a timely message and celebrate diversity in filmmaking; 
ashley judd, salma hayek and annabella sciorra â€” three women who publicly accused harvey weinstein of sexual misconduct â€” took the stage together to introduce the segment.

when jimmy kimmel kicked off this year's oscars, he promised a light of positivity" during his opening monologue. during the third act of sunday's show, that promise materialized when the academy devoted a segment to honoring the  and time's up movements and highlighted the diversity in movie-making in the last year. "many spoke their truth and the journey ahead is long, but slowly a new path has emerged," said judd, referencing the women and men who have come forward to say  and time's up. those voices have joined together to create a "mighty chorus," she added. judd shared a hope that the next 90 years of the academy awards will "empower these limitless possibilities of equality, diversity inclusivity, intersectionality â€” that's what this year has promised us." hayek then introduced a pre-taped segment highlighting some of this year's most diverse and ground-breaking filmmakers â€” from greta gerwig and dee rees to  duvernay and kumail jiani â€” whom she referred to as "unstoppable spirits who kicked ass and broke through bias perceptions against their gender racer and ethnicity to tell their stories." jimmy kimmel said "we need to set an example and if we can work together here to stop sexual harassment in the workplace, women will only have to deal with harassment all the time, at every other place they go." perhaps speaking to critics of hollywood award shows who believe they have grown "too political," kimmel explained that the night's show would include brave and outspoken voices of the   and  movements in hopes of spurring positive change. "this is a night for positivity," he declared before rattling off all the names of nominees who had the potential to break or set new records if they were to win.

text:
two years ago today, i left georgia college. hereâ€™s a story about why. 
a few weeks before i left, i found my old phone that i used while dating my abuser, that had text messages from her on it where she admitted to sexually assaulting me. soon after, i went back to the title ix office to try and reopen the case i originally started that june. the title ix coordinator was weirdly nonchalant when she saw me. she was like â€œhow is your semester going? how is everything? itâ€™s so nice to see you!â€ as if we were old friends chatting about life. i told her i was doing very badly and had not been able to function since we last spoke. i was failing all of my classes. i saw my abuser almost daily and was having frequent panic attacks and nightmares. i was diagnosed with acute stress disorder and later ptsd. i had an eating disorder relapse directly due to not being able to deal with everything. 
the title ix coordinator looked at the text messages and later told me that there should be enough evidence to reopen the case, getting my hopes up, but a few weeks after, i was told there was still â€œinsufficient evidenceâ€. insufficient evidence, even though i had a lengthy confession typed out in clear english from madelyn. insufficient evidence. insufficient evidence. i had an entire diary on a password protected flash drive that listed all the trauma i went through during the relationship. i had pages and pages of notes on my computer detailing more things she did and titled it at the time with things like â€œpublic administration class notesâ€ so when my abuser would go through my notes, she wouldnâ€™t suspect anything and click on it. i had pictures of the bruises. witnesses of how isolated i became. i had her own poetry where she confessed how violent and manipulative she was. had evidence to show she lied in her original statement to the title ix coordinator. i had everything i needed to show that she abused me. all georgia college did was protect madelyn, telling me i was never allowed to say her name and what happened, unless i wanted to be charged with â€œretaliationâ€. i left because georgia college decided it was in their best interest to protect my abuser over me.

today we're kicking off our #startupsunday series where we highlight
startups run by women and the underrepresented.

we start our first #startupsunday monthly series by featuring accompany, a company in which women represent 40% of the growing team!

uses artificial intelligence and machine learning to be your virtual
chief of staff, providing you with all of the information you need about anyone you are meeting with in a given day. accompany had raised over $40m from top investors and most recently was acquired by cisco for $270 million.  wowza!

text:
i had the privilege of attending a jewish bat mitzvah celebration yesterday. during the silent period dedicated to personal reflection, i read this one from the prayer book. constant internal chatter overwhelms my everyday experience as an incest and illness survivor. the new neurological connections being formed, while old ones are being challenged. the general life questions that we all ask: what do i want, where am i going, who am i? all flood in and out and back around in me. so, it was a great reminder to let my internal voices find rest. i hope that for you, too. .
.
.
#rest #rejuvenation #love #peace #metoo #recovery #simplicity #wisdom #selfhelp #help #cure #spirituality #truth

text:
just had the best sunday morning conversation around our kitchen table wearing my "we are the village" shirt.

i want you all to know, no, need you all to know, that you are welcome here.

my vision is a world with more community and less walls. a world filled with "me too, brother" and "i hear you, sister". a world of see a need fill a need instead of waiting for a politician, celebrity or "someone more qualified" to step in.

the saying "it takes a village" is repeated often because it's true. raising children, being married, going to college, living life takes a village. it takes a community of people who are out for each other's good instead of out for themselves.

so, i want you to know you have permission to be your true self. you have the power to change someone's life for the better. you have the power to give to others who need. you have the power to be the light for those who are lost and just need someone to say "it's okay. you're welcome here."
.
friends, we are the village. together we can. and you are always, always welcome at my table, any time.

text:
i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). (facebook official page, 23/06/2013) * read the whole article in the site.

text:
i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). (facebook official page, 23/06/2013) * read the whole article in the site.

text:
i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). (facebook official page, 23/06/2013) * read the whole article in the site.

text:
what i hold to be true most others donâ€™t. or people are afraid to speak up / go against the grain. my girlfriend and i were talking about our own #metoo moments amongst other things and she said â€œwe have to be the ones to say â€˜no moreâ€™ â€œ and itâ€™s true. some of us were chosen to lead the pack.

last year i went backwards a bit in regards to my own sexuality. after 12yrs of being sexually shamed by the one person who should have desired me the most, i had finally come into my own sexual and sensual power.

then an event took place and i thought. maybe i asked for it. maybe it was how i carried myself. maybe itâ€™s because i was drinking. all the maybes went through my head.

text:
i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). (facebook official page, 23/06/2013) * read the whole article in the site.

text:
alright. it's time i speak out. 
i got a message for the man i hung out with in november. the one i trusted as a friend for 3 years. a guy who helped me get through the 8th grade. 
just cause we were fond of each other. just because i hung out with you. that november. at the park does not mean that i wanted you to take that from me. i went home with you for a soda, not to have my very body and rights taken from me under you. 
do you hear me? 
do you see this message? 
are you still hurting girls? are you still thinking about me? and about how i told you no? are you still fantasizing about my pained face as i was about to cry from pain? can you still feel the fear of my shaking body? my breathe holding itself back? can you hear the choke in my throat from wanting to cry and break down?? can you still hear it? can you still see it?? ladies. be careful. most men will never understand. they can't comprehend the pain and emotional scars lefts behind from being raped. some can try, some will sympathize. 
others will ask for every gory detail. 
you tell them that you are not their porn. 
that your horror story is not their get off. 
some men will tell you to stop crying, cause they are stuck up. tell them to ask their mother or sister is they had been raped. ask them if they would want their beloved mothers or sisters degraded under another guy that way. 
if they still don't understand then they aren't going to understand. 
women who are silenced i won't tell a soul. 
cause i understand that after that you feel like your soul has left your body. 
this was my story. #metoo

text:
i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). (facebook official page, 23/06/2013) * read the whole article in the site.

i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). text:
kissing toxic masculinity goodbye

the age of the patriarchy is being re-evaluated right now, in the wake of the #metoo movement.
and it's time we get real about how the patriarchy actually hurt men, too.

men have been made to believe that the feminine aspects of themselves such as their feelings, empathy, and tears must never be seen, or they will be labeled as weak.

or even worse, be called a â€œpussy.â€ because vaginas, women, and the feminine have been rendered weak, and powerful women are labeled as witches, which has become synonymous with evil.
no man wants that as an identity, even as a joke...
when for women, it's a reality we are fighting to shift every day.

so, it's time. it's time to #freethefeminine in all.

freeing the feminine is not just about women. it liberates the feminine within men, too... which topples toxic masculinity culture and allows men to express themselves fully.

both men and women are rising up to use their voices and do the work to free the feminine, and step into our most healthy expression... are you?

to join the movement, click the link in our bio now.

#freethefeminine #wearefree

text:
i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). (facebook official page, 23/06/2013) * read the whole article in the site.

â€œiâ€™ve got a lot to tell you.â€ i collapse into the blue chair next to the window, my normal seat. you sit across from me. notebook in lap, pen between your fingers. i look up at you, only for a second. then i focus on the pattern of the worn-down carpet, what used to be a floral rug had been worn down to a frayed wad of fabric. i listen to the clock tick in the background. â€œwell iâ€™m all ears.â€ you reply. â€œpromise me you are going to listen, and not get mad for not telling you sooner.â€ a look of panic quickly flashes across your face, then a look of concern, then curiosity. guilt flushes over me, a lump forms in my throat. i take a shaky breath, already feeling tears well up in my eyes. â€œhow do i explain this, without sounding insane?â€ you smile at that; the tension seems to release a bit. â€œremember to breathe, deep breaths.â€ you remind me. â€œright.â€ i reply. â€œstart from the beginning, you donâ€™t have to tell me anything you arenâ€™t comfortable sharing yet.â€ well, i would tell you. but itâ€™s not that easy.
i remember what happened, six years ago. itâ€™s the only thing i really can remember. 
i feel like iâ€™m watching my younger self in third person. sheâ€™s walking down the hallway, clenching the strap of her backpack. she walks into her classroom, sets her backpack on the rack and slumps down. next to her, is a boy with blonde hair. their mouths are moving, i canâ€™t make out what they are saying. iâ€™m watching from the other side of the door. the boy moves closer to the younger version of me. he reaches out to touch her, he places his hand above the zipper of her jeans. he slips his hand into her pants, the look on her face disturbs me. 
i suddenly feel sick and gross, like i got sneezed on. i feel trapped, it feels as if the world was caving in, my heart is pounding, my palms become slick with sweat.

text: when my godfather/uncle passed, my mother and i flew to san antonio for his funeral. at the time i was too young to drive ğŸ˜¨ one of my cousins took me out to show me where he worked as a dj at a country night club called "cowboys." there he bought me a t-shirtâœ” as a souvenir to remember the night we had together ğŸ˜± he also wrote on a bar napkin (pic 3) @hidefrodeo what he had done to me; in his words. 36 years later i heard from his dad, a retired police officer from san antonio, the "incident" was my fault ğŸ˜¨ i never told my parents or anyone for that matter because i was so embarrassed......my cousin, who was old enough to work in a night club vs too young to drive; my fault??? i'm very glad i saved the bar napkin, my only proof âœ”in his handwriting. smh #metoo

text: i had a great time at the #spiritawards yesterday. thanks @filmindependent ! i am grateful for the recognition and exposure that @thetalemovie got, thanks largely to hbo, #metoo and #timesup. but as awards season comes to a close, i'd like to give a shout-out to all the great films that didn't get the awards, the nominations, the box office, the press, the recognition. every year, there are so many, including many wonderful films i've been lucky enough to be a part of. i'm thankful too that @nancythemovie was recognized at the spirit awards, but even that level of recognition often doesn't translate to people seeing the movie. it's sometimes puzzling why certain films get attention and others that are equally good or better do not. i guess it's about getting the right alchemy--right time, right place, right distributor, right distribution execs, right publicist, and...money. what a crazy business we work in! congrats to all the winners, all the nominees, and especially to all the people who made great films that few saw or wrote about. may they continue to be discovered and watched for years to come! #oscars #fyc

text: regardless of what we are lead to believe, there is no shame in being sexually assaulted. the shame is on the aggressor. healing takes time, itâ€™s coming to terms that it was not your fault, itâ€™s recognising that fighting / fleeing / freezing / folding are all ways your body did its best to protect yourself. it will be hard, and if youâ€™re supporting a friend or a loved one going through this healing process the best way to react is to just be understanding. accept how they feel. do not victim blame. do not dismiss. listen. itâ€™s not easy discussing assault, and reactions from those trusted enough for the victim to come to are often respected dearly and taken to heart. be mindful when youâ€™re approached, and empathise.

Â© heather sten for wsj. magazinealexandra waterbury.alexandra waterburyâ€™s posture is perfect. itâ€™s the kind people beg their yoga teachers to make possible. the dancer, 21, lifts her chin in a way that unfurls her 5-foot-9-inch frame to its fullest. with her watery blue eyes and long blond hair, she looks like a music-box ballerina in a cream turtleneck. for three years, waterbury practically lived at lincoln center, dancing up to 36 hours a week at the school of american ballet (new york city balletâ€™s affiliate academy) and graduating with an offer to turn pro with the washington ballet. today, her professional dance career is over. sheâ€™s now midway through her second year of college at columbia university, and at this moment, fresh from a visit to her statistics tutor. she flops down a large black tote bag, the urban staple for women with one foot in young-adult lives and another in professional ones. â€œi feel like kids on disney channel,â€ she says of the life she now wants to avoid. â€œthey grow up with this immense pressure to be perfect all the time. and thatâ€™s when things explode.â€waterburyâ€™s own world exploded after she filed a lawsuit in september against nycbâ€¦

text:
*trigger warning*
this piece was the very first thing i wrote about my grandpa. i wasnâ€™t writing for what people might think when they read this; i wrote because i had to. i needed to pour out everything that was in my mind, if not i thought iâ€™d explode. everything in this comes from my heart and soul. when i look back and read it now, it hurts less and less every time. saying something out loud or writing about it, makes the experience 100x more real. but watch out because doing so, can and will hurt a person when they begin to feel all those suppressed emotions, resurface. once i began to think about my abuse again, everything felt so real. i was living in this constant battle with myself. all these thoughts and images were clouding my brain after so much time had passed. where did they come from? why are they here? no matter how hard i tried, i couldnâ€™t stop thinking of my past and how it has affected every decision iâ€™ve made. when you feel this way, you have to push yourself to have hope and not let those horrible memories take control over you. every part of you will be affected if you give your demons power.  iâ€™m still dealing with the pain and trauma from my years of abuse. every day, i try my best to remain positive but not every day is a good one. i learned that you cannot let your past, control the present, and your future. by giving all your energy to past events, you are draining yourself. you are almost forcing yourself to relive every incident that has occurred and a person can not live this way. iâ€™ve been there. now that i am sharing a part of myself with the world, i hope other survivors will read this and resonate with my words. i donâ€™t want us to dwell on what happened but rather, find peace in reality of it all. you are not alone, i am just like you. if you ever want to talk with me about anything, i am here. #thecultivatedfool
name: Simply & Positively

sacred sisterhood:
a coven for modern wise-women to rise together and stand stronger.
our sisterhood is here to support all women, at any stage and age. itâ€™s a safe space to be seen and to let down the walls so you can express yourself fully and stand in your power. each month we gather in san francisco during the different moons to honor the sacred bond of sisterhood and ourselves.
by coming together in circle we reclaim what has been missing in our lives - community and authentic connection. we reclaim the right to be perfectly imperfect, to share, love and heal ourselves and the sisterhood wound.
through our own journeyâ€™s we have witnessed the power of women coming together and how quickly women go from strangers to sisters. and we are devoted to creating a sacred space where everyone can be accepted and seen. a place where you can fully express yourself without any judgement.
nothing's a coincidence and you finding this page means you were meant to find us, and us to you. we are connected through the sacred bond of sisterhood. we see you. we are one. i am you. you are me.
it is time for women to come together so we can stand stronger and rise together. it is time to let down the walls and rebuild a future for our daughters to be fully self-expressed. a future where their blood will yet again be celebrated. it starts with us. with supporting each other to rise. it starts with circle. with standing united. energy exchange $33, link in bio. â¤ï¸

black bloggers chicago was created with the belief that content creators of color have influence and impact on the culture.  we are committed to supporting and assisting black content creators from chicago and the chicagoland area in the building and development of their blogs and websites by providing educational resources and to connecting content creators to brands to form long lasting and mutually beneficial partnerships.

text: lean in. iâ€™m going to let you in on one of foster careâ€™s dirty little secrets. itâ€™s something no one wants to confess to but i refuse to let the shame of not immediately loving a child gain ground in my life-or in yours. iâ€™ve spent sleep deprived weeks wishing the newborn in my care would just stop crying. iâ€™ve found myself in a full panic attack as the shuffle of toddler feet in footie pajamas found its way to my side of the bed morning after morning. iâ€™ve raised eyebrows in jaded disposition at the suggestion of strangers that they could never give them back. oh, you could. some are easier to say goodbye to than others. iâ€™ve counted down hours to a transition for a kid i couldnâ€™t stand to be in the same room with. iâ€™ve gone thru the motions time and time again and literally begged god to let me love a son or a daughter. itâ€™s all true. itâ€™s all human. and itâ€™s all part of the process of refining our souls. itâ€™s ugly. itâ€™s raw. itâ€™s real. and so few fosters feel safe to say #metoo.  but iâ€™ll shine light on the darkest places so you can be okay finding freedom to be flawed and failed. do not believe the lie that this journey should feel good or look light. itâ€™s broken me. itâ€™s brought out rage. itâ€™s revealed the dark in me that i thought only belonged to other people. we all need a savior and for some of us on the frontlines, the preconceived ideas can lead straight to our destruction. itâ€™s okay to not love right away. itâ€™s okay to not like (ever). itâ€™s okay that everyone else thinks your kiddo is an angel and they canâ€™t believe you feel the way you do. itâ€™s okay to not share with those who wouldnâ€™t understand anyway. but i know. i see. iâ€™ve lived it. iâ€™m living it. and iâ€™m praying you find safety in knowing youâ€™re not alone. #noshame #realfosterlife #fostercare #thisisfostercare #itisokay #behuman #runtojesus

text:
black history month fact # 24: tarana burke @taranajaneen (born 1973) is an entrepreneurial civil rights activist from the bronx, nyc. here career highlights include...
-created the non-profit organization "just be" for young black girls ages 12 to 18 (2003).
-created the viral movement "me too" #metoo @metoomvmt to raise awareness of the pervasiveness of sexual abuse and assault in society (2006).
-moved to philadelphia to work for several non-profits (2008).
-served as a consultant for the motion picture "selma" (2014).
-named time magazine's @time person of the year (2017). #blackhistorymonth #blackhistorymonthfacts #blackhistorymonth2019 #blackhistoryfacts #themoreyouknow #blackhistory #blacklivesmatter #365black #blackpride #blacklegends #entrepreneur #professor #tedxspeaker #motovationalspeaker #entertainer #artistcareercoach #dancecompany #dancecompanyconcerts #model #gay #gays #gaysofinstagram #instagay #gayguy #singers #blackneighborhoods #blackprosperity #blackhistorynow #millennialentrepreneurs @oprah

text:
warning: feminist content

alright. yes this is an ad, just like the gillette gender statement was an ad. even though i believe this is a brilliant and necessary message, letâ€™s not think about the endorsement for a moment. the motivation and personal experience described in this ad is all too familiar to any female or femme identifying person. all too often expectations, assumptions, and judgments are used to keep women quiet. these labels, i.e. crazy, dramatic, emotional, are placed on women every day. being reduced to a label leads to fear and a sense of powerlessness. i personally experience a paralysis that comes from not believing i have the right to call someone out on their bad behavior. this ad at least calls attention to the judgements placed on women. with awareness, hopefully, we can all become more aware and conscious of when we label ourselves, and others, in a damaging way. letâ€™s challenge each other to wake up to the bad habits perpetuated by the tradition of gender roles. be accountable. .
.
.

â€”
the purpose of the black experience exhibit & the women behind the lens!
the black experience explores the perspectives of black people of color. capturing real people in their element. the mission is to simply give as many black people the opportunity to not only share their experiences but the space to start a conversation. bernice johnson the creator behind the exhibit, teamed up with creatives tiana smith, a digital content creator, who uses her art and platform to explore her personal and artistic journey as a black, queer, femme woman. and chris lowe, a photographer who creates with intention. aiming to capture the concepts, the visuals, and the stories of her subjects. creating a picture that resonates and connects with others. the black experience aims to celebrate inclusivity, educate people, and create a positive dialogue that is reflective of bpoc. creating an overall feeling of togetherness.

text:
50,000+ calls are made to the rape crisis hotline in ontario per year. in niagara region there is a 12-18 month wait to meet with a counselor in regards to sexual trauma and abuse. we do not have enough counselors in niagara to meet the needs of the staggering number of survivors. in order to provide the help we need to support the programs offering it. @niagara.sexual.assault.centre has a small team of incredible counselors that do far more than what should be asked of them. they need our support to be able to expand and offer help to all those who need it. having more counselors in niagara would bring down the excruciating wait time and more people would be helped sooner. i waited 15 months before i got the call that it was my turn to be heard and to be given the tools to heal. now that i am on my journey to healing my mind and my soul i can't help but to think of the survivors seeking help who called after me, still waiting. .
@niagara.sexual.assault.centre
www.niagarasexualassultcentre.com
24/7 crisis hotline 905-682-4584
.
#survivorscantwait #supportsurvivors #metoo #niagara #niagarafalls #stcatharines #welland #thorold #pelham #portcolborne #fonthill #grimsby #ourhomestc #enough

text:
i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). (facebook official page, 23/06/2013) * read the whole article in the site.

text:
sometimes my house is not a home but a prison
from the front yard it looks like a lovely family
but the grass isn't always greener on the other side
because on the inside all my thoughts are denied 
and when this happens there's a battle with the beast and we collide
there is no arguing with the beast ,he's a brick wall and will win in the end , sadly with your pride....
the only thing you can do is run and hide or perfectly abide

he will make fun of you,call you a disgrace
you will want to be anywhere but this place!!!!
because whenever you see him ,you can see his soul is black and filled with hate 
thereâ€™s a nonstop war between us ,there's no time make peace
or have time to calm down and discuss
because the things it has put me through are unjust
it wants everything in that moment and if it doesn't get it it will erupt!!! what happens when he erupts, i become a punching bag !!! how long will this happen,how long will i tolerate this ? how long ??????##enddomesticviolence ##voiceofthevoiceless ##activist ##changinglives ##carolmotolofoundation ##carolmotolo ##metoo ##metoomovement ##broken ##healing ##africa ##lesotho ##bbcafrica ##survivorstalescarolmotolo ##
